T1  - A normal cumulative conception rate after human pituitary gonadotropin.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/s0015-0282(16)45021-1
A1  - Healy, D L
A1  - Kovacs, G T
A1  - Pepperell, R J
A1  - Burger, H G
Y1  - 1980//
N2  - Forty consecutive women were treated with human pituitary gonadotropin to induce ovulation. Thirty-seven patients (93%) ovulated and thirty (75%) conceived on at least one occasion. The cumulative conception rate for the series equaled that of the general population. Women with a past history of anorexia nervosa had the shortest average time to pregnancy. Of patients who did not conceive, four represented failures of patient selection in that they withdrew from treatment for a variety of psychiatric and social reasons, and six represented failures of treatment, not becoming pregnant despite the induction of ovulation. It is concluded that realistic goals for a contemporary human gonadotropin program include induction of ovulation in all patients and a cumulative conception rate equal to that of the general community.
